\begin{center}
	{\Large{\bf{INTRODUCTION}}}\\
\end{center}
Travelling Salesman Problem (TSP) is a classical and most widely studied problem in Combinatorial Optimization. This problem belongs to a category referred to as NP-complete ie. if its solution can be guessed and verified in polynomial time \cite{william2012cook}. It has been studied intensively in both Operations Research and Computer Science since the 1950s as a result of which a very large number of methods were studied to solve this problem. The idea of the problem is to find the shortest route of salesman starting from a given city, visiting n cities only once and finally arriving at the origin city \cite{bektas2006multiple}. The problem can be sketched on graphs with each city becoming a node. Assuming a complete weighted graph, edge lengths correspond to the distance between the attached cities \cite{taha2011operations}.\\
\\
The TSP occurs in countless forms with some applications of engineering that include Vehicle routing scheduling problems, integrated circuit designs, physical mapping problems, and constructing phylo-genetic trees.\\ \\
Following are the constraints of a TSP problem: 
\begin{itemize}
\item The total length of the loop should be a minimum. 
\item The salesperson cannot be at two different places at a particular time. 
\item The salesperson should visit each city only once.
\end{itemize}

\vspace{-0.3cm}
\begin{figure}[htpb]
\centering
\includegraphics[height=4.5cm,width=6.8cm]{fig1.png}
\vspace{-0.7cm}
\caption{A graph with weights on its edges}
\end{figure}

\hspace{-0.7cm}
According to the above figure, the problem lies in finding the shortest path to pass through all vertices at-least once. \\
For example, both Path1 (ABCDEA) and Path2 (ABCEDA) pass through all the vertices. However it can be seen that the total length of Path1 is 24, whereas the total length of Path2 is 31.
